[split] scrooge: secondary struct class constructors without _passthroughFields for backwards compatibility It was reported to me that enabling _passthroughFields generation by default broke some code in science that uses jackson to deserialize json to thrift.  jackson uses reflection, and passes in null for the _passthroughFields argument, since it doens't know about scala default values.  Consequently, the resulting struct generates NPEs.

[split] bump birdcage to scrooge-maven-plugin/scrooge-generator 3.10.2, parent poms to 0.1.6 In the latest version of scrooge (since 3.7.0):   - flexible schema support (passthrough fields) is now turned on by default;   - support for larger structs that would previously result in a scalac failure with bytecode indices > 16k;   - removed deprecation warnings on FutureIface, FinagledClient, FinagledServer, until the replacements are fully baked;   - fixed import issue with unions;

[split] scrooge-generator: simplify synthesized structs For synthesized service method arg and results structs, we don't need to generate separate struct-trait/Immutable-class/Proxy-trait classes and field-blob getters and setters, as they don't really make sense for classes that client code never uses directly.  For exception classes, the trait/Immutable/Proxy classes also don't really make sense, although the field-blob getters and setters might be useful.  This slims down the generated code for thrift services quite a bit.

[split] scrooge-generator: don't backquote scala identifiers in Enum.valueOf string constants

[split] scrooge-generator: produce slimmer code, remove _passthroughFields from object apply method Attempting to bump the entire birdcage to the current version of scrooge-generator, I ran into a problem where several projects would cause scalac to hit a GC limit.  I've made some tweaks to generate a combination of less code (by removing duplication with read/write methods), code that produces less bytecode (by reducing calls to `clone` which explodes into a lot code with the all the default field values), and code that produces fewer anonymous classes (by removing calls to TFieldBlob.capture).

[split] scrooge-generator: default passthrough value, valid method names Attempting to update the birdcage to the lastest scrooge-generator, I discovered two issues:   - each struct trait defines an abstract _passthroughFields method; some projects extend this trait directly, and no longer compile with passthrough enabled by default, because the method is not implemented.  To fix this, the trait now defines a default implementation that returns an empty set;   - my changes to break large methods up into smaller methods to avoid the 65kb jvm method size limitation produce invalid code when a field in a struct doesn't explicitly specify the field ID, because it assigned a negative field ID, and I used the field ID as part of the method name, resulting in invalid method names like "readField-2".  To fix this, I switched from using the field ID to always using the field name in the method name.

[split] scrooge-serializer: easier serializer builder for historical compatibility reasons, the serializer code in scrooge-serializer is all trait based, with no concrete classes.  this means to use a BinaryThriftStructSerializer, you have to either mix the trait into another class or create an anonymous class, which adds both syntactic overhead as well as hundreds of additional class files throughout our code base.
[split] scrooge-maven-plugin: check for null from Artifact.getDependencyTrail

[split] scrooge: support larger structs ibis thrift is not compilable with the current version of scrooge, because it contains some large structs that results in large methods that exceed the 16-bit addressing within a single jvm method.  this change breaks up the two largest methods (decode and unsetField) into smaller chunks, and pushes the boundary on struct size back.

[split] scrooge: allow oneway scrooge needs to be able to work with thrift files that use oneway, so rather than rejecting any thrift with the oneway modifier, just treat a oneway method like a normal void method.  async invocation via Futures is close enough to the intent of oneway that this is a better tradeoff, and allows us to move more projects onto scrooge.

[split] scrooge: passthrough field improvements There were a few issues discovered with the initial implementation of passthrough fields in scrooge which this review attempts to address.  Namely:   1) TTransport is stateful wrt encoding/decoding, and is thus a poor choice for wrapping binary field data;   2) TField doesn't implement Object.equals or Object.hashCode, making it a poor choice for a HashMap key;   3) Without a general way to get/set any field, passthrough or not, with binary, there was fragility around code written to handle fields as passthrough, as that code would stop working after recoming against the latest thrift schema file, when a formerly passthrough-field would be promoted to first-class

[split] scrooge-ostrich: add thriftProtocolFactory as val The generated ThriftServer class has a thriftProtocolFactory field that some subclasses use.  Adding this val makes the transition to OstrichThriftServer easier.

[split] remove use of deprecated generated ostrich ThriftServer The generated ostrich-based ThriftServer class that scrooge generates is deprecated and going away soon.  Short-term, you can use scrooge-ostrich's OstrichThriftServer for the same functionality, although longer terms, all projects should be switching to twitter-server.  This review removes the use of the generated ThriftServer for all projects in the birdcage that are using the current version of scrooge.  Some projects unnecessarily include the "--ostrich" in their pom, and those resulted in trivial pom changes.  For projects actually using the generated ThriftServer, I've switched you over to the non-generated OstrichThriftServer.

[split] scrooge: fixed whitespace eating in strings ThriftParser extends RegexParsers.  RegexParsers calls a whitespace parser before each sub-parser, to automatically consume and discard whitespace.  The stringLiteral parser was composed of 3 sub-parsers, start quote, body, and end quote, which means the whitespace parser was getting invoked after the start quote and before the end quote.  This means whitespace within a string would get eaten, and if that whitespace was a line comment, the ending quote would get gobbled up as part of the line comment.  The fix is to use a single regex to match the entire string, quotes and all, and then strip the quotes off after the match.
